[[Image:Céčkaéčka.jpg|200px|thumb]]
'''Céčka''' ({{lang-en|C's}}) (singular céčko) were plastic toys from [[Czechoslovakia]] popular in the 1980s and 90s, formerly used as parts of door hangings.<ref name=RadioPrague>{{cite web | title=Inconspicuous plastic toy that has made it to the National Museum | url=http://www.radio.cz/en/article/94729 | work= | publisher=Radio Prague | date=2007-08-23 |author=Fraňková, Ruth | accessdate=2009-08-25}}</ref>

== History ==
The initial intention was to use Céčka as buckles for women's clothing, but it was a failure.<ref name=CzechTV>{{cite web | title=Retro v médiích. Všichni jsme Retro | url=http://www.ceskatelevize.cz/program/detail.php?idp=10204191786&day=1250892000&time=12:32&ch=24&id=1488&deid=2582 | work= | publisher=[[Czech Television]] |author=Vrbová, Martina | date=2009-05-22 | accessdate=2009-08-25|language=cs}}</ref> The next attempt was to use them as parts of door hangings, but this did not succeed either.<ref name=CzechTV /> The real interest, which was born among the Czechoslovak children, set off ''Céčková horečka'' (''Céčka fever'').<ref>{{cite web | title=Céčka jsou nejoblíběnější na Moravě | url=http://www.radio.cz/cz/zpravy/96500 | work= | publisher=Radio Prague | date=2007-10-15 | author=Nyklová, Martina | accessdate=2009-08-25 | language=cs | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080419053726/http://www.radio.cz/cz/zpravy/96500 | archive-date=2008-04-19 | dead-url=yes | df= }}</ref> From 1984, Céčka became scarce materials of considerable value (for children) almost instantly.<ref name=autogenerated1>{{cite web |title= Céčka boli v ČSSR vzácne ako tvrdá mena |url= http://spravy.pravda.sk/cecka-boli-v-cssr-vzacne-ako-tvrda-mena-dxb-/sk_domace.asp?c=A090802_125431_sk_domace_p12 | work= | publisher=Pravda.sk |date= 2009-08-02 |author= Pacherová, Soňa |accessdate= 2009-08-28 |language=sk}}</ref> The basic shape is a letter ''C''.<ref>{{cite web |title= Blasts from the past |url= http://www.radio.cz/en/article/106543 | work= |publisher= Radio Prague | date=2008-07-27 |author=Fraňková, Ruth | accessdate=2009-08-28}}</ref>

Plastic parts can be chained, and they were also used in several games, for instance, one similar in principle to [[pitching pennies]].<ref name=autogenerated1/> It also inspired [[Michal David]]'s song ''Céčka, sbírá céčka'' (C's, she collects C's).<ref name=RadioPrague /> Céčka are also mentioned twice in the song ''Pochodové cvičení'' by Czech singer and songwriter [[Slávek Janoušek]].<ref>[http://www.slavekjanousek.cz/cd_a06_13.htm Text of the song - slavekjanousek.cz]{{dead link|date=August 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>

