This is a list of '''longest prison sentences''' ever given to a single person, worldwide. Listed are instances where people have been [[Sentence (law)|sentenced]] to jail terms in excess of a [[maximum life span|human lifetime]]. Note that many national legislations worldwide do not allow for such sentences.
==Prisoners sentenced to more than one life imprisonment== {{main|List of people sentenced to more than one life imprisonment}}
{| class="wikitable sortable" cellpadding="4px" |- ! style="width:76px;"| Name ! style="width:75px;"| Sentence start ! style="width:75px;"| Sentence term ! style="width:100px;"| Country ! class="unsortable"| Description |- | [[Terry Nichols]] | 1995 | 162 life sentences plus 93 years without parole | {{Hs|United States}} {{flagcountry|United States}} | Convicted of 161 counts of [[first degree murder]], first degree [[arson]], and conspiracy by the state court of [[Oklahoma]] for his part in the [[Oklahoma City bombing]] of April 19, 1995: also sentenced in federal court for terrorism and eight counts of involuntary manslaughter. Record for most consecutive life sentences ever given to a single individual. |- | [[Abdullah Barghouti]] | 2004 | 67 life sentences plus 5,200 years without parole | {{Hs|Israel}} {{flagcountry|Israel}} | Commander of [[Hamas]]' [[Al-Qassam Brigades]] and one of its chief bomb makers. Sentenced for the death of 66 Israelis, he is held in [[solitary confinement]] and denied visits. |- | [[Gary Ridgway]] | 2003 | 49 life sentences <small>(48 of them without parole)</small> plus 480 years | rowspan="2" | {{Hs|United States}} {{flagcountry|United States}} | [[Serial killer]] known as the "Green River Killer", who confessed to have murdered 71 prostitutes between 1982 and 1998. |- | Loi Khac Nguyen | 1991 | 49 consecutive life sentences without parole | Surviving perpertrator of the [[1991 Sacramento hostage crisis|1991 Good Guys siege]]. Convicted of three murders, 11 attempted murders and 35 counts of kidnapping. |- | [[Martin Bryant]] | 1996 | 35 life sentences plus 1,035 years without parole | {{Hs|Australia}} {{flagcountry|Australia}} | [[Mass murder]]er who pleaded guilty to murdering 35 people and injuring 23 others in the [[Port Arthur massacre (Australia)|Port Arthur massacre]], a shooting spree in Port Arthur, Tasmania, Australia on 28 April 1996.<ref name="smh2">{{cite news |last1=Wainwright|first1=Robert|last2= Totaro |first2=Paola|url=http://www.smh.com.au/national/a-dangerous-mind-what-turned-martin-bryant-into-a-mass-murderer-20090427-ajk4.html|title=A dangerous mind: what turned Martin Bryant into a mass murderer?|work= |location=Sydney|publisher=''[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]''|date=April 27, 2009|accessdate=November 1, 2014}}</ref> Sentenced to the maximum penalty of life imprisonment for each murder, and an additional 1,035 years for wounding 23 people, shooting at 14 other people with the intention to kill, four counts of theft of a motor vehicle, three counts of arson and one of kidnapping. |- |}
==Prisoners not sentenced to life imprisonment== These sentences differ technically from sentences of [[life imprisonment]] in that the designated jail times have specific lengths, although in practical terms they may serve the same purpose.
===Prisoners sentenced to more than 1,000 years in prison=== {| class="wikitable sortable" cellpadding="4px" |- ! style="width:76px;"| Name ! style="width:75px;"| Sentence start ! style="width:75px;"| Sentence term ! style="width:100px;"| Country ! class="unsortable"| Description |- | [[Chamoy Thipyaso]] | 1989 | 154,005 years | {{Hs|Thailand}} {{flagcountry|Thailand}} | World's longest sentence for [[corporate fraud]] according to ''[[Guinness World Records]]'' 2006. She defrauded more than 16,000 Thais in a [[pyramid scheme]] worth $204 million at the time.<ref name="csmonitor">{{cite news |last=Belsie|first=Laurent|url=http://www.csmonitor.com/Business/new-economy/2009/0629/madoffs-sentence-big-but-not-141078-years|title=Madoff's sentence: big, but not 141,078 years|work= |location= |publisher=''The Christian Science Monitor''|date=June 29, 2013|accessdate=January 1, 2014}}</ref> However, the Thai law of the time specified that those convicted of fraud could not serve more than twenty years in prison, and she was released after only eight.<ref>Chungsiriwat, Grissarin (2013). ''Thailand At Random.'' Didier Millet. p. 83</ref> |- | Otman el-Gnaoui | rowspan="3"| 2007 | 42,924 years | rowspan="3"| {{Hs|Spain}} {{flagcountry|Spain}} | rowspan="3"| Sentenced for their roles in the [[2004 Madrid train bombings]]. Under Spanish law, the maximum sentence that any of them can serve is 40 years.<ref name="theguardian1">{{cite news |last=Hamilos|first=Paul|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2007/nov/01/spain|title=Mass murderers jailed for 40 years as judge delivers verdicts on Spain's 9/11|work= |location= |publisher=''[[The Guardian]]''|date=October 31, 2007|accessdate=September 11, 2014}}</ref> |- | [[Jamal Zougam]] | 42,922 years |- | Emilio Suárez Trashorras | 34,715 years |- | Charles Scott Robinson | rowspan="3" | 1994 | 30,000 years | rowspan="3" | {{Hs|United States}} {{flagcountry|United States}} | Longest jail term to a single American on multiple counts. Sentenced to 5,000 years for each of the six counts against him.<ref name="latimes">{{cite news |last=Hubbard|first=Amy|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2012/aug/15/nation/la-na-nn-long-prison-sentences-20120815|title=Top 10 Longest Prison Sentences in the World|work= |location=Los Angeles|publisher=''[[Los Angeles Times]]''|date=August 15, 2012|accessdate=November 1, 2013}}</ref> |- | Allan Wayne McLaurin | 20,750 years | Accomplice of Darron Bennalford Anderson. Upon appeal, his sentence was reduced by 500 years.<ref name="huffingtonpost">{{cite news |last=Banner|first=Adam|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/adam-banner/castro-technically-still-_b_3922691.html|title=Ariel Castro's 1,000 Year Sentence Isn't the Longest Sentence on Record|work= |location= |publisher=''[[The Huffington Post]]''|date=September 14, 2013|accessdate=January 1, 2014}}</ref> |- | Darron Bennalford Anderson | 11,250 years | Greatest amount of jail time given as a result of an appeal. Found guilty of crimes ranging from rape of an elderly woman in [[Tulsa County]], to larceny, robbery and kidnapping, and sentenced to 2,250 years. He appealed, was reconvicted, re-sentenced and received an additional jail term of 9,500 years, later reduced by 500 years.<ref name="knowqout">{{cite news |last= |first= |url=http://www.knowqout.com/history-culture/outrageous-prison-terms-given-to-people/|title=Outrageous Prison Terms Given to People|work= |location= |publisher=''Know-Q-Out''|date=July 25, 2013|accessdate=November 1, 2013}}</ref> |- | Carlos Antonio Carias López | rowspan="4"| 2011 | 6,060 years | rowspan="5"| {{Hs|GUA}} {{flagcountry|GUA}} | rowspan="5"| Former soldiers sentenced for their roles in the 1982 [[Dos Erres massacre]].<ref>http://www.elmundo.es/america/2011/08/02/noticias/1312295006.html</ref><ref>https://www.bbc.com/news/world-latin-america-17349774</ref> |- | Daniel Martínez Martínez | 6,060 years |- | Reyes Collin Gualip | 6,060 years |- | Manuel Pop | 6,060 years |- | Pedro Pimentel Ríos